title: The title of the paper is: **TYCOV: An Open-Source, Year-Long Behavioral Study of Human Ability to Detect AI-Generated Images**

pico_elements.population: 1,217 unique participants who completed forced-choice classifications on a web application.
pico_elements.intervention: Detecting AI-generated images within a balanced set of stimuli.
pico_elements.comparison: Detecting real photographs within the same balanced set of stimuli.
pico_elements.outcome: Detection accuracy, specifically aggregate accuracy, class-conditional accuracies for real vs. AI images, error patterns (confusion matrix), and longitudinal accuracy trends over 55 weeks.

quality_scores.justification: The research is a longitudinal observational study, which is a type of cohort study. It collected data from a self-selected cohort of 1,217 participants over a 55-week period to measure their ability to distinguish AI-generated images from real ones. As an observational study without a randomized control group, it fits the description of a Cohort Study, which is assigned a 'Medium' quality score according to the provided rubric.
